@Andrzej

Spanish, being the language of nearly two dozen countries, has a great variety of local versions.  The words LLANO and PAMPA both refer to flat, grassy areas that in English we would call plains, but PAMPAS are more specifically used to describe the flatlands of the Southern Cone of South America, and most often, Argentina in general.

LLANO can be used to describe the same lands, but is less likely to be used for something singled out as Argentinean.  Plains of Colombia, for example, would be called LLANOS, but those in Argentina more commonly would be called PAMPAS.

